eThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Admin/BkFill/Default_image_group/2012/6/25/1340627692744/Line-of-Duty-003.jpg","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/38hf6","standfirst":"Line Of Duty | Gordon Behind Bars | Coming Here Soon: Greece, Bust And Broken | Ethan Hawke On&nbsp;Macbeth | Hit &amp; Miss | Imagine","hasStoryPackage":"false","lastModified":"2012-06-29T10:33:31Z","body":"<h2><strong>Line Of Duty</strong><br />9pm, BBC2<br /></h2><p>Vicky McClure, Lennie James and Gina McKee head a cast list so impressive that even the \"and Neil Morrissey\" at the end doesn't spoil the overall \"serious drama\" effect. This five-part drama tackles police corruption and it's quickly apparent who the dodgy coppers are, as they're much more interesting than the honest ones. It's off to a fine start: in only a few minutes we're knee-deep in botched police raids, faked reports, unreported crimes and cover-ups. This opening episode lays out the numerous characters efficiently, with a few big twists kept for the end. <em>Phelim&nbsp;O'Neill</em></p><h2><strong>Gordon Behind Bars</strong><br />9pm, Channel 4<br /></h2><p>Jamie's cornered the school dinner market, so Gordon Ramsay heads to Brixton prison for his do-good mission. His aim is to spend six months teaching the inmates to cook so they can set up a business selling food on the outside. \"None of these reprobates has a clue how to cook,\" he concludes after a disastrous egg-scrambling incident. But he soon gets into his stride, dropping the F-bomb all over the place as his \"bad boy brigade\" bake fairy cakes. <em>Hannah Verdier</em></p><h2>Coming Here Soon: Greece, Bust And Broken<br />9pm, BBC3<br /></h2><p>In a new series, Stacey Dooley investigates the consequences of financial meltdown in three countries: Greece, Ireland and Japan. She starts in Greece and soon discovers how bleak things are – unemployment, food handouts, scavenging in Athens. Dooley's presenting style is to get involved and report back how she feels about it; whether this approach provides a reliable analysis of the country's problems is down to whether you prefer touchy feely human interest stories or facts and figures delivered by reporters with serious expressions. <em>Martin Skegg</em></p><h2><strong>Ethan Hawke On&nbsp;Macbeth</strong><br />9pm, BBC4<br /></h2><p>The Hollywood actor takes an in-depth look at the part he's always wanted to play. Those who retch at the sight of thesps earnestly pontificating should look away because Ethan does a lot of brow-furrowing here. Former Macbeths and Lady Macbeths, including Antony Sher and Harriet Walter, describe their approach to the roles, and a curiously Yank-heavy cast of academics discuss the psychology of a guy who skewers a king to death because three crones told him to and his pushy wife wouldn't shut up about it. <em>Julia Raeside</em></p><h2>Hit &amp; Miss<br />10pm, Sky Atlantic<br /></h2><p>The concluding part of the Paul Abbott-created series, bringing home the realities of juggling working life as an assassin with the stresses of being a transsexual raised by fairground folk. Chloë Sevigny doesn't convince in the lead role as Mia but neither is she risible, bringing a seething presence to her part. In this final episode, Mia discovers, at some painful cost, that \"family has nothing to do with blood\". Much music tonight, in an episode whose visual language borders on that of the rock video. If Hit &amp; Miss fails, it at least does so interestingly. <em>David Stubbs</em></p><h2><strong>Imagine</strong><br />10.35pm, BBC1<br /></h2><p>Occasionally, Alan Yentob's Imagine films can seem merely decorative, or too in thrall to celebrity culture. In this first film of the new series nothing could be further from the truth: it profiles the production of The Two Worlds Of Charlie F, a new \"documentary play\" that stars veterans of the war in Afghanistan. It's a striking work that uncovers scars physical and mental, personal and political. As one character says: \"When we leave Afghanistan, a little bit of it stays with us, or us with it.\" <em>John Robinson</em></p><p>• This article was amended on 29 June 2012. The original referred to those who wretch at the sight of thesps pontificating. This has been corrected.</p>","headline":"TV highlights 26/06/2012","trailText":"<p>Line Of Duty | Gordon Behind Bars | Coming Here Soon: Greece, Bust And Broken | Ethan Hawke On&nbsp;Macbeth | Hit &amp; Miss | Imagine</p>","newspaperPageNumber":"22","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Guardian","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Admin/BkFill/Default_image_group/2012/6/25/1340627692744/Line-of-Duty-003.jpg","wordcount":"582","commentable":"false","internalContentCode":"392146908","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"6334348","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Phelim O'Neill, Hannah Verdier, Martin Skegg, Julia Raeside, David Stubbs and John Robinson","newspaperEditionDate":"2012-06-26T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"1764591","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2012-06-28T18:59:01Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2012/jun/25/line-of-duty-preview","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/tv-and-radio/2012/jun/25/line-of-duty-preview","tags":[{"id":"culture/series/watchthis","webTitle":"Watch this","type":"series","sectionId":"tv-and-radio","sectionName":"Television &amp; radio","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/series/watchthis","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/culture/series/watchthis","references":[]},{"id":"culture/television","webTitle":"Television","type":"keyword","sectionId":"tv-and-radio","sectionName":"Television &amp; radio","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/television","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/culture/television","references":[]},{"id":"tv-and-radio/tv-and-radio","webTitle":"Television & radio","type":"keyword","sectionId":"tv-and-radio","s