isit where she tries to ameliorate his situation. An extraordinary tale indeed. <em>Julia Raeside</em></p><h2><strong>Simón Bolivar Orchestra – Live From Stirling</strong><br />9pm, BBC4</h2><p>Traditionally held up as an example of how youth leaders can turn around lives with the transformative power of classical music, the Simón Bolivar Orchestra of Venezuela perform a concert in Scotland as part of the London 2012 festival. It's a strange meeting of occasion and geography but this is likely to be another impressive showing from the maturing orchestra (technically, it's no longer a \"youth orchestra\"). The youth element here comes from Raploch's Big Noise project, a Scottish cousin of the original South American educational \"Sistema\". <em>JR</em></p><h2><strong>Playhouse Presents: Psychobitches</strong><br />9pm, Sky Arts 1</h2><h2><strong>Dead Boss</strong><br />10.30pm, BBC3</h2><p>If the second part of last week's double bill seemed slow, here's a cracker of an episode to drive the series along. Anna Crilly (Magda in Lead Balloon) steals the show as German cannibal Gertrude Wermers, who comes to the prison on an exchange programme, much to Top Dog's delight. In the office, there's more news about the mystery of the lottery syndicate, and Mr Bridge's widow makes her presence felt by removing the Nespresso machine. <em>Rebecca Nicholson</em></p>","headline":"TV highlights 21/06/2012","trailText":"<p>The Men Who Made Us Fat | The Boy They Call Fish: Extraordinary People | Simón Bolivar Orchestra Live From Stirling | Playhouse Presents: Psychobitches</p>","newspaperPageNumber":"22","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Guardian","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/6/19/1340129888670/The-Men-Who-Made-Us-Fat-003.jpg","wordcount":"362","commentable":"false","internalContentCode":"391869483","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"6320224","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Jonathan Wri