linka Survivor Stories | You Gotta Eat Here! | Celebrity Bedlam","hasStoryPackage":"false","lastModified":"2014-06-26T17:20:48Z","body":"<h2><strong>Who Do You Think You&nbsp;Are?</strong><br />9pm, BBC1</h2><p>The celebrity genealogy series returns, and first to take a journey into the past is&nbsp;Samantha Womack, AKA Ronnie Mitchell out of EastEnders. Her research focuses on two of her great-grandparents. Alexander Cunningham Ryan, Womack learns, was injured in the first world war. More unusually, euphonium theft and personal disgrace also featured in his life history. As for great-grandma Beatrice Garraud, she initially proves to be an elusive figure. Cue Womack, with much help from experts, turning detective as she tries to learn why her forebear, whose mother was still alive, lived in an orphanage. <em>Jonathan Wright</em></p><h2><strong>Celebrity Big Brother: Launch Show</strong><br />9pm, Channel 5</h2><p>Civilian Big Brother passed in a bland blur, so now it's time for the celebrity version. Brian Dowling whips the crowd into a frenzy in tonight's live launch show. Of course the definition of \"celebrity\" is as loose as ever – the show is open to anyone who has grabbed headlines for two minutes, or spoken to someone who did. Still, it's always more entertaining than standard Big Brother. Who's in?&nbsp;The lineup will be revealed tonight, but Samantha \"Hey, I'm beautiful\" Brick is among those rumoured. <em>Hannah Verdier</em></p><h2><strong>The Culture Show at the Edinburgh Festival Part 1</strong><br />10pm, BBC2</h2><p>Sue Perkins takes over presenting duties in this first of three shows from the Scottish arts festival. Guests include comedian Mark Thomas talking about his stand-up, Harry Hill showing off his art, and Miriam Margolyes, who checks out the Catherine the Great exhibition at the National Museum of Scotland. Plus there's sure to be a rolling conveyor belt of comics, musicians and performers to further liven things up. <em>Julia Raeside</em></p><h2><strong>Death Camp Treblinka Survivor Stories</strong><br />9pm, BBC4</h2><p>The publicity for this documentary describes Treblinka as a \"forgotten death camp\", which might be pushing things, given that Holocaust studies is an ever-burgeoning concern and the Nazis are a staple of factual TV. Still, there is a remarkable story here of how Samuel Willenberg and Kalman Taigman escaped the killing facility in occupied Poland (responsible for the deaths of more than 800,000 Jews) during a revolt in 1943. One joined the ill-fated Warsaw uprising in 1944 as an act of vengeance, while the other appeared at the trial of Adolf Eichmann in Jerusalem in 1961. <em>Martin Skegg</em></p><h2>You Gotta Eat Here!<br />9pm, Good Food</h2><p>It can only be his hypermetabolic manner as a presenter that prevents John Catucci from tipping the scales at 40st. He's an enthusiastic junk-food connoisseur and in this new series visits the Canadian joints known for making the best high-calorie food in the business, from Stoney's Pizza parlour to the Rock Cod Cafe, from chocolate peanut butter cheesecake to slow-roasted lamb sandwiches, all served in heroic portions. Just watching this is liable to make you put on weight. <em>David Stubbs</em></p><h2><br />Celebrity Bedlam<br />10pm, E4</h2><p>Fresh from Sellotaping fruit to Big Brother contestants' faces, Lee Kern turns his attentions to the subject of travel and adventure in his celeb-pranking show. His innocent face and deadpan attitude serves him well as he preys on his unsuspecting victims. This week, Lee poses as the world's only blind racing driver, persuades hapless boybander Andy Scott-Lee to break the news that scientists have found the iceberg that hit the Titanic and convinces Blue Peter presenter Zoe Salmon that she's presenting a show to be shown on plasma screens in the South Pole. <em>Hannah Verdier</em></p>","headline":"TV highlights 15/08/2012","trailText":"Who Do You Think You Are? | Celebrity Big Brother: Launch Sho