e to the sometimes bloated \"event\" nature documentary. <em>Martin Skegg</em></p><h2><strong>Our War</strong><br />9pm, BBC3</h2><p>From Ross Kemp's terrified excursions in the region to journalists embedded with serving personnel, the war in Afghanistan has not been short on quality documentary coverage. Our War, returning for a second series, attempts something that must have been a bureaucratic nightmare: the story of life serving in Helmand Province, in the words and photos of the soldiers who are serving there. This opening episode joins the Duke Of Lancaster's Regiment as they protect a vital road link. <em>John Robinson</em></p><h2><strong>Revenge</strong><br />9pm, E4</h2><p>There are shows that tread a fine line where they have to string things out as long as possible while still throwing the viewer an occasional bone to keep them watching. Lost and The Killing were both magnificent at maintaining that balance, and now you can add Revenge to the list. In one of the show's finest episodes to date, Emily works up a typically complicated scheme to get the other Emily (Amanda, the real Emily) to skip town. It's a plan that has unexpected consequences and makes us wonder whether the person we're rooting for is worth our sympathy or is instead as callous as those she's after. <em>Phelim O'Neill</em></p><h2><strong>The Riots: In Their Own&nbsp;Words</strong><br />9pm, BBC2</h2><p>\"I can remember the air crackling with static,\" says Sergeant Henry Beresford of the British Transport Police. But even the most grizzled copper could surely not have guessed how terrifying the next few hours would be in Croydon, with officers forced to break into a burning building to warn its residents to evacuate. For all the criticism that's been directed at Britain's police over their handling of last summer's riots, a documentary gathering officers' testimony reminds you that it was ordinary men and women who were called upon to hold the thin blue line. <em>Jonathan Wright</em></p><h2>Toast Of London<br />10pm, Channel 4</h2><p>Matt Berry, familiar to viewers of The IT Crowd, takes the lead in this comedy pilot, written by Arthur Mathews. Steven Toast is a 40-something actor trying to right himself after a few setbacks (recent divorce; a starring role in a play so controversial people attack him in the street). Even given his considerable talents, it's hard to see how he can get his career and his life back on track by auditioning for a TV producer who is currently in jail for Holocaust denial. An excellent premise, but one which gets lost among the rather low-rent gags. <em>JR</em></p>","headline":"TV highlights 20/08/2012","trailText":"Don't Blow The Inheritance | Nature's Microworlds | Our War | Revenge | The Riots: In Their Own Words | Toast Of London","newspaperPageNumber":"22","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Guardian","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/8/17/1345214950963/riots-in-streets-of-totte-003.jpg","wordcount":"579","commentable":"false","internalContentCode":"394857391","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"6556032","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Ali Catterall, Martin Skegg, John Robinson, Phelim O'Neill and Jonathan Wright","newspaperEditionDate":"2012-08-20T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"1789435","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2012-08-22T18:59:02Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2012/aug/19/riots-in-their-own-words","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/tv-and-radio/2012/aug/19/riots-in-their-own-words","tags":[{"id":"culture/series/watchthis","webTitle":"Watch this","type":"series","sectionId":"tv-and-radio","sectionName":"Television &amp; radio","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/series/watchthis","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/culture/series/watchthis","references":[]},{"id":"culture/television","webTitle":"Television","type":"keyword","