outhwatering mozzarella and tomato sauce on the menu, and she also makes a pilgrimage to Bologna to pick up tips from the locals. <em>Hannah Verdier</em></p><h2><strong>Mission to Mars: a&nbsp;Horizon Special</strong><br />9pm, BBC2<br /></h2><p>In the leadup to the planned landing on Mars of Nasa's Curiosity rover on 6 August, Horizon is here to tell how incredible and difficult the project will be. It's almost as though the engineers wanted to get their excuses in first in case it all goes wrong. The statistics, though, are sobering: two-thirds of missions to Mars have ended in disaster. As you might guess, sending a delicate craft millions of miles across space into an unpredictable atmosphere is enormously complex. Curiosity's procedures have to work first time, or Nasa's $2.5bn investment could simply vanish. <em>Martin Skegg</em></p><h2><strong>Coming Up</strong><br />11.05pm, Channel 4<br /></h2><p>This year's Coming Up season continues in its bid to showcase the work of new writers and directors with Spoof or Die, a timely effort directed by Prasanna Puwanarajah, who also made a short film for the opening ceremony of&nbsp;the Olympics. It's the story of 16-year-old Craig, a&nbsp;Belfast boy with a keen interest in the city's political history, and his partner in truancy Nicky, who has just moved over from England. <em>Rebecca Nicholson</em></p><h2><strong>Nature's Microworlds</strong><br />8.30pm, BBC4<br /></h2><p>This week Nature's Microworlds looks at the Amazon rainforest, less a Microworld – as previous episodes on the Serengeti and the Galapagos Islands have explored – than its own functioning ecosystem. It makes its own weather, for God's sake. Faced with the impossibility of summing up such a place&nbsp;in 30 minutes, this week's programme is spoilt for choice in terms of bafflingly immense facts and&nbsp;impressive footage of oxbow lakes stuffed full of two-metre-long giant otters, some of the rainforest's most prolific predators. <em>Ben&nbsp;Arnold</em></p><p></p><h2>Revenge<br />9pm, E4<br /></h2><p>As Revenge progresses, its already tenuous relationship with reality lessens, and the show is the better for it. It's got to the stage now where it's like some high-camp, super-soap opera with conniving women running rings around clueless, effete men. There's even a semi-mystical Japanese CEO who sidelines as a revenge mentor for Amanda/Emily. In a world where so much episodic TV is predictable, who could honestly say they saw that coming? The increasingly psychotic Tyler steals the show this week, blackmailing and bitching his way to the top and then entertainingly flipping out when it goes a bit wrong for him. <em>Phelim O'Neill</em></p><p></p><h2>First Cut: Britain's Oldest Stand-Up<br />10pm, More4<br /></h2><p>Chelsea Pensioner Jack Woodward followed his father into the armed forces and, later, showbusiness, becoming a BBC warm-up man in peacetime. But his last gig, in a working men's club in the north, was in 1968. And now, aged 90, he says: \"My biggest problem with standup comedy is standing up.\" This touching little film follows Jack's progress as he prepares to open for Ed Byrne at the Hammersmith Apollo. Will he remember his lines? \"I've still got what it takes to get a lady into the bedroom. A stair lift.\" <em>Ali Catterall</em></p>","headline":"TV highlights 30/07/2012","trailText":"Simply Italian | Mission to Mars: a Horizon Special | Coming Up | Nature's Microworlds | Revenge | First Cut: Britain's Oldest Stand-up","newspaperPageNumber":"22","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Guardian","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2012/7/27/1343406053305/Michela-Chiappa-Simply-It-003.jpg","wordcount":"564","commentable":"false","internalContentCode":"393710492","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"6466472","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Hannah Verdier, Martin Skegg, Rebecca Nicholson, Ben Arnold, Phelim O'Neill and Ali