, Alex and Peter try to make ends meet in a world where imported food is scarce. Manor Farm is a hive of activity this week. Ruth recruits a Pig Club and gets cracking on a lovely swill, as well as picking up tips on how to steal petrol. Alex and Peter are occupied with silage, but disaster strikes when they realise the cows have enjoyed a premature munch on their sugar beets. Meanwhile, the ladies of the Hampshire WI get busy with the preserves. <em>Hannah Verdier</em></p><h2>Screenwriters – The Bafta And BFI Lectures<br />8pm, Sky Arts1</h2><p>The last in this series of masterclass lectures from prominent writers from film and TV may well be the best of the lot, featuring an insight into the inner workings of the inimitable Charlie Kaufman, the mind behind such knotty greats as Adaptation and Eternal Sunshine Of The Spotless Mind. Kaufman argues here that a production-line culture in Hollywood has stunted the creative output of many of his peers, and calls for a shift towards original screenwriters. Easier said than done, one fears, but a fine sentiment nonetheless. <em>Gwilym Mumford</em></p><h2><strong>Good Cop</strong><br />9pm, BBC1<br /></h2><p>This is a drama with the premise of a bad US cop movie, but which has been cast and played like the best kind of UK drama. Warren Brown continues to do a great job as John-Paul, a slightly anonymous-looking Liverpool policeman whose vigilante actions to avenge his murdered co-worker are beginning to give him a few worries. It's a tense drama, that finds John-Paul not so much losing the plot as pursuing tangential storylines – none of which are particularly well-advised. <em>John Robinson</em></p><h2><strong>The Audience</strong><br />9pm, Channel 4<br /></h2><p>On paper the concept for this new series is nuts. One person who faces a life-changing decision is literally followed around by 50 people for a week as they go about their lives. The audience observe, ask questions and meet people involved in the dilemma, before coming to a conclusion as to what should be done. As TV it works remarkably well, as people's different opinions are brought to bear, though the filmmakers are skilful in carving a narrative and know exactly what to do with the emotional capital generated. First up is dairy farmer Ian Wainwright, who must decide whether to stay at his family's farm or to start a new life. <em>Martin Skegg</em></p><h2><strong>The InterCity 125: The&nbsp;Age Of The Train </strong><br />9pm, BBC4<br /></h2><p>Perhaps best-known due to Jimmy Savile's long-running ad campaign, or for inspiring one of Ben \"Double Seat\" Elton's most memorable routines, the InterCity 125 was introduced by British Rail in 1976 with the aim of revitalising its commercial fortunes and to make travelling by train a more appealing experience for the public. Here we hear the story of how newly-installed BR bigwig Peter Parker set out to update Britain's rail industry, even if the tenacious telly cliche of old-fashioned compartment cars would live on for a while longer. <em>Mark Jones</em></p><h2>Stephen Hawking's Grand Design<br />9pm, Discovery</h2><p>\"Curving space and time may sound tricky to wrap your head around … but it's not.\" Effectively, here's where Stephen Hawking gets down with the kids. Or at least, tones it down to the point where phrases like \"Check it out!\" and \"Quantum physics – I told you it was weird!\" become commonplace. It's unnerving initially, but at least underlines the fact that this science gubbins is supposed to be fun. In this first episode, Hawking covers everything from gravity to the finely named luminiferous aether, while asking \"What is this universe stuff anyway?\" <em>Ali Catterall</em></p>","headline":"TV highlights 13/09/2012","trailText":"Wartime Farm | Screenwriters – The Bafta And BFI Lectures | Good Cop | The Audience | The InterCity 125: The&nbsp;Age Of The Train | Stephen Hawking's Grand Design","newspaperPageNumber":"22","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publicatio