inent so charmed her that she promoted him to be her \"munshi\" or teacher. Their relationship horrified her court: for a member of the lower races to enjoy parity with them was unthinkable in the 19th century. As this drama-documentary shows, a confrontation ensued before the Diamond Jubilee. <em>David Stubbs</em></p><h2><strong>Beautiful Minds</strong><br />9pm, BBC4<br /></h2><p>Professor Richard Dawkins is the most influential evolutionary biologist of his generation but is as well known these days for his outspoken attacks on religion. Here, he talks about his childhood in Africa and how his first encounters with Darwin's work initially left him underwhelmed, his scientific influences, and his campaigning days at Berkeley. It's all a lead up to his seminal work, The Selfish Gene, which turned evolutionary theory on its head and made him into a science superstar, but also flamed a controversy that's followed him ever since. <em>Martin Skegg</em></p><h2><strong>Justified</strong><br />9pm, 5USA<br /></h2><p>This show has perhaps television's finest rogues' gallery, from nightmarish stone-cold killers down to comical (but dangerous) buffoons. Tonight we get them all. Hapless stooge Dewey Crowe loses something close to his heart, while Dickie Bennett is not happy with his depleted \"inheritance\". Meanwhile, an understaffed Boyd faces off to city slicker Quarles and there are signs that Devil is getting far too ambitious. That's a lot of crime for one small county. <em>Phelim O'Neill</em></p><h2>Mountain Of Ice<br />9pm, PBS<br /></h2><p>The Vinson Massif is well-named. It's the highest mountain in Antarctica, and this documentary records the first attempt to ascend it from its eastern side, with the climb team lugging a less-experienced film crew and an unspeakable amount of scientific kit along with them. Although this expedition took place in summer 2001, the beauty and hazards of the terrain haven't dated. Along the way, the team dispense their views on previous expeditions: claiming, for example, that Scott's disastrous polar expedition of 1912 failed entirely due to the leader's hubris. Spectacular, and informative too. <em>John Robinson</em></p><h2>Turtle Boy: A BodyShock Special<br />10pm, Channel 4</h2><p>Six-year-old Didier lives in a hamlet in Columbia. He and his family are forced to live in isolation due to an extremely rare condition called congenital melanocytic nevus. This caused a mole to grow on his body to the extent that it covered 40% him; it looked like a shell, earning him the nickname Turtle Boy (the superstitious villagers blamed his mother for conceiving him during an eclipse). This documentary follows Didier as he prepares for an operation which, though risky, may give him the chance of a normal life. <em>MS</em></p>","headline":"TV highlights 25/04/2012","trailText":"<p>Our Food | Queen Victoria's Last&nbsp;Love | Beautiful Minds | Justified | Mountains Of Ice | Turtle Boy: A Bodyshock Special</p>","newspaperPageNumber":"22","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Guardian","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Admin/BkFill/Default_image_group/2012/4/24/1335266839495/Victoria-And-Albert-Queen-003.jpg","wordcount":"538","commentable":"false","internalContentCode":"389095086","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"6092459","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Jonathan Wright, David Stubbs, Martin Skegg, Phelim O'Neill and John Robinson","newspaperEditionDate":"2012-04-25T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"1735289","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2012-04-27T19:00:01Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2012/apr/24/queen-victorias-lastlove","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/tv-and-radio/2012/apr/24/queen-victorias-lastlove","tags":[{"id":"culture/series/watchthis","webTitle":"Watch this","type":"series","sectionId":"tv-and-radio","sectionName":"Television &amp; radio","webUrl":"http://www.the