lic characters, even including trade union leaders. With latterday cultural fragmentation and the thin spread of increasingly nondescript \"celebrities\", the job of an impressions show such as this, starring Morgana Robinson and Terry Mynott, becomes all the harder. It is telling that they often have to announce who it is they're doing. Still, this is as capable as could be expected; in the first episode, Bear Grylls tries out his survival skills in the suburbs, while David Attenborough studies at close hand the remarkable animal that is Frankie Boyle. <em>David Stubbs</em></p><p></p><p></p><h2>Dexter<br />10pm, FX<br /></h2><p>It seems we can all go home early as <a href=\"http://fxuk.com/shows/dexter/about\" title=\"\">Dexter</a> has apparently solved this season's murder mystery. Seeing Travis returning to the scene of his latest crime, Dexter spots the proud look of a fellow serial killer easily enough. But we know more about these Doomsday Killers than Dexter does, and it looks as if the audience is going to be several steps ahead for some time. This isn't great for the show; Dexter, for all his faults, has always been the smartest person in play. Now we have to watch him slowly catch up with the viewers. Painful. <em>Phelim O'Neill</em></p><p></p><h2><strong>Alan Carr: Chatty Man</strong><br />10pm, Channel 4<br /></h2><p>Tulisa Contostavlos, from The X Factor and the now-defunct R&amp;B triumvirate N-Dubz, is among Alan Carr's guests for the return of Chatty Man, now entering its eighth series for Channel 4. Since her last appearance, a grubby MPEG of her has been distributed on the internet. Will Carr confront the grainy, pixelated elephant in the room? His chatty credentials hang in the balance. <em>Ben Arnold</em></p><p></p><h2>30 Rock<br />10.30pm, Comedy Central</h2><p>Six series in, <a href=\"http://www.comedycentral.co.uk/shows/30-rock-season-06/episodes/30-rock-season-6-episode-05/video/a-jack-off-30-rock-605-759280/\" title=\"\">30 Rock</a> is still among the smartest sitcoms out there, its fast-cut style bearing comparison with animated comedy such as The Simpsons and Family Guy. Tonight, Liz decides to settle a contract dispute with Jack by using an old tape of his own negotiating techniques. Meanwhile, Tracy and Jenna help out a shy barmitzvah boy whose only experience of girls is \"a Japanese videogame where you slap prostitutes to death\", and Kenneth the page is feeling unwanted, though as Jack observes, he needn't be too downhearted – \"He's a white male with hair – the sky's the limit!\" <em>DS</em></p>","headline":"TV highlights 27/04/2012","trailText":"Unreported World | Lip Service | Very Important People | Dexter | Alan Carr: Chatty Man | 30 Rock","newspaperPageNumber":"30","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Guardian","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2012/4/26/1335440953772/Unreported-World-003.jpg","wordcount":"562","commentable":"false","internalContentCode":"389263780","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"6103560","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Martin Skegg, Hannah Verdier, David Stubbs, Phelim O'Neill and Ben Arnold","newspaperEditionDate":"2012-04-27T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"1736801","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2012-04-29T18:30:01Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2012/apr/26/unreported-world-lip-service-vip","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/tv-and-radio/2012/apr/26/unreported-world-lip-service-vip","tags":[{"id":"culture/series/watchthis","webTitle":"Watch this","type":"series","sectionId":"tv-and-radio","sectionName":"Television &amp; radio","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/series/watchthis","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/culture/series/watchthis","references":[]},{"id":"culture/television","webTitle":"Television","type":"keyword","sectionId":"tv-and-radio","sectionName":"Television &amp; radio",